Question: What is (are) Autoimmune hemolytic anemia? Answer:<<<SEP>>>Autoimmune hemolytic anemia (IAE) is a condition in which the proteins in the liver accumulate in the body during long-term use of certain foods. IAE generally occurs in young people who ingest two or more small amounts of a specific type of food every day, often without enough food for one to have symptoms of chronic illness.1 These foods are often made from certain high-fat foods. They are considered unprocessed foods when consumed by patients (see page 36). The term includes:

Tarrant, streptococcal bacteremia, and noncellulose streptococci;

Pertussis and sclerosing fusiform encephalitis;

Nautilus influenzae type b virus (also known as Salmonella Typhimurium); and

The flu vaccines.2

Question: What is (are) Amyloidosis AA? Answer:<<<SEP>>>Amyloidosis is a group of diseases in which high levels of amyloid produce a low risk of disease for the person. Amyloidosis is characterized by low levels of amyloid and low risk of disease in the immune system, such as inflammatory bowel disease and lymphomas. Other factors that influence inflammation include:

Reduced levels of amyloid to lower levels;

Higher levels of amyloid when cells grow in a small area and when there are less amyloid or amyloid cells in the site, such as when cells were removed in the laboratory;

Lymphoma or tumors;

Lymphoma or tumors are very rare when the number of amyloid cells is low, but is still present sometimes in the lymphatic system, such as atopic dermatitis, lymphospasm;

Certain forms of inflammatory bowel disease
